list.item:
Anaphylactic reactions [see 

                           Warnings and Precautions (5.1)

                        ]

CDAD [see 

                           Warnings and Precautions (5.2)

                        ]

Gastrointestinal: Black hairy tongue, and hemorrhagic/pseudomembranous colitis. Onset of pseudomembranous colitis symptoms may occur during or after antibacterial treatment [see 

   Warnings and Precautions (5.2)

].

Hypersensitivity Reactions: Anaphylaxis [see 

   Warnings and Precautions (5.1)

]. Serum sickness–like reactions, erythematous maculopapular rashes, erythema multiforme, Stevens-Johnson syndrome, exfoliative dermatitis, toxic epidermal necrolysis, acute generalized exanthematous pustulosis, hypersensitivity vasculitis, and urticaria have been reported.

Renal: Crystalluria has been reported [see 

   Overdosage (10)

].

text.paragraph:
Amoxicillin is an antibacterial drug. [see 

                              Microbiology (12.4)

                           ].

Metabolism and Excretion: The half-life of amoxicillin is 61.3 minutes. Approximately 60% of an orally administered dose of amoxicillin is excreted in the urine within 6 to 8 hours. Detectable serum levels are observed up to 8 hours after an orally administered dose of amoxicillin. Since most of the amoxicillin is excreted unchanged in the urine, its excretion can be delayed by concurrent administration of probenecid [see 

   DRUG INTERACTIONS (7.1)

].
